# Relegation Manager — Project Rules

## What this project is
- **Relegation Manager**: A Championship Manager 01/02–style clone in React. The player manages a struggling team fighting relegation (take over at gameweek 19, 19 games to survive).
- **Stack**: Vite + React. Main app in `src/relegation-manager.jsx` (component `RM` + `LiveMatch`). Entry: `src/main.jsx` → `<RM />`.

## Core design philosophy
- **Authenticity to CM 01/02 is the top priority** — UI and feel should match that experience.
- Favour **simple, readable code** over clever or over-engineered solutions.
- UI should feel like CM: **functional, data-dense, no modern UI fluff**.
- This is a **passion project**, not a production SaaS app.

## Visual theme
- **Dark navy background** (#0a0f1e, #0e1220, or similar).
- **Gold/amber accent** (#ffd700) for highlights, selected items, headers.
- Light text on dark backgrounds.
- Minimal borders, clean table layouts.
- **Utilitarian fonts** — spreadsheet-like, not decorative (e.g. Tahoma).
- **No** rounded corners, gradients, or modern card-based layouts.

## Game systems (existing / target)
- **Tactics:** Formation, team instructions (pressing, tempo, width, etc.).
- **Squad selection:** Starting XI, subs, roles. UI should resemble CM’s pitch view (drag/drop or slot-pick).
- **Match engine:** Text-based commentary with scoreline and events (goals, cards, injuries, subs) — scrolling text feed, not 2D/3D pitch.
- **League table:** Standard P/W/D/L/GF/GA/GD/Pts.
- **Transfers/squad:** Appropriate for a relegation-battling side (e.g. January window).

## CM 01/02 UI conventions
- **Tabbed navigation** between screens (not sidebar or hamburger).
- **Tables** are the primary data display — not cards or tiles.
- Selected rows/items **highlighted in gold/amber**.
- **Minimal icons** — text labels preferred.
- **Compact, information-dense** layouts.

## Code conventions
- **React:** Functional components and hooks only (`useState`, `useEffect`, `useMemo`, `useRef`). `useState`/`useReducer` for state — no Redux unless complexity clearly demands it.
- **No TypeScript** — plain JSX.
- **CSS:** In component file (inline `style={{}}` + embedded `css` string) or a single stylesheet. No CSS-in-JS libraries.
- **Game logic:** Pure where possible; keep separated from rendering.
- Single-file components are fine when small; extract only when there’s clear repetition.
- **Naming:** Preserve existing abbreviations when editing (e.g. `pt` = player team, `pIdx` = player index, `fix` = fixtures, `wk` = week).

## Data and state (technical)
- Game state lives in `RM`: `teams`, `pIdx`, `wk`, `fix`, `news`, `tab`, training, tactics, etc.
- **Persistence:** `window.storage` for auto-save and career history; it may be undefined.
- **Globals:** `TEAM_DATA`, `TEAMS` set on league choice; avoid adding new globals.
- **Squad:** `pt.sq`, `pt.xi`, `pt.sub`, `pt.form` (`.s` and `.xy`). Match: `preGen` (player match), `simFast` (others); then `finishMatch` for tables, fitness, morale, board/scout, sacking. Weeks: 19 = appointment, 24 = window close, 38 = season end; relegation = 18–20.

## What NOT to do
- **Don’t modernise the UI** — no Material UI, Tailwind cards, or “clean modern” redesigns.
- **Don’t over-abstract early** — extract patterns only when there’s clear repetition.
- **Don’t add dependencies** unless truly necessary.
- **Don’t use AI-slop placeholder text** — use realistic football data (real team names, player names, etc.).
- When adding/changing code: prefer small, localised edits; use existing classes (`cm-btn`, `cm-panel`, `cm-sunken`, `cm-table`) and keep `autoSave` / `saveCareer` consistent for any feature touching match flow or saves.
